				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: Question on atk, ac, resist caps<a name="55685"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Aug 9 04 1:08 AM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>Hmm, here's the short version : (I'm not going to summarise by expansions though)
<br />

<br />
Resists - The higher the better. When you hit 500 to all unbuffed, you can probably stop working on resist gear. The level of the mob casting on you is also important; the higher the mob, the better chance it has of success. Hence, as expansions come out, and higher and higher level mobs are designed, you need more and more resists in order to effectively resist spells/AE's etc.
<br />

<br />
Attack &amp; AC : These are both interrelated. I'll explain it from a PC point of view, but it works the same for mobs as well. If your AC is lower than the mobs attack, it will do more damage. The closer you get your AC to that of the mobs attack value, the better your mitigation will become. Once your AC is higher than the mobs attack, you get greately reduced returns for increasing your AC even more AGAINST THAT MOB, because you already have pretty  much maxed your mitigation against it.  The important point to note is that this 'soft cap' that people talk about (which is the point at which your AC is just over the mobs attack, after which more AC has much smaller benefits) varies from mob to mob.  So the 'soft cap' is really only applicable on a mob by mob basis. 
<br />

<br />
As  more expansions were released, to make content more challenging, mobs attack and max damage were increased, (see Kunark/velious) which made a higher AC more important, and increased the average 'soft cap' for mobs in those expansions.  However, as a change, when Luclin was released, the mobs attack wasn't upgraded quite so much as the mobs AC. (see places like Ssra, Deep, VT) What this meant was that players were often hitting for far lower damage simply because the difference between their attack rating, and the mobs AC was quite large. Luclin was the expansion where melee DPS classes (rogue, monk, ranger) really needed to focus on increased worn attack.
<br />

<br />
Since then, SoE appears to be heading the path of lower AC and HPs, with higher attack (compared to the earlier expansions) but correspondingly better gear to combat this.  The net result is that players need to be constantly increasing their AC in order to keep reaching the 'soft cap' in AC of new mobs. 
<br />

<br />
In summary (and I'm going off an only somewhat reliable memory here) the highest soft caps for general xp mobs in the main expansions were : 
<br />

<br />
Original - 1000AC 
<br />
Kunark - 1200 AC
<br />
Velious - 1400 AC
<br />
Luclin - 1800-2000AC (I'm a bit fuzzy on this one) 
<br />
PoP - around 2200AC
<br />
GoD - I dunno, I don't think the numbers are in for this one yet =p
<br />

<br />
Anyway, I'm sure that I've made some errors and mistakes in this post (especially on the numbers) but the general principle is sound. 
<br />
If your AC is higher than the mobs attack, you'll take less damage, and there is little benefit to increasing your AC vs that mob.  
<br />
If your attack is higher than the mobs AC, you'll do more damage (on average) than if your attack is lower than the mobs AC. 
<br />
Remember, the 'soft caps' on attack and AC vary from mob to mob, so there is no easy figure to give you. The numbers above are rough guides to aim for in AC depending on what expansion you spend most of your time in. 
<br />
I have no idea of the attack figures, but my general principle for both AC and attack is you can't go wrong by adding more <img src="/skins/default/images/emotions/emotion-2.gif" border="0" alt="Big Smile" hspace="2" /> </span></td>
